Two methods with takes any number of predicates and returns new function which applies given predicates to it arguments.

* `_.and` returns true if each of given predicates returns true for arguments.
* `_.or` returns true if some of given predicates returns true for arguments.

Simple implementation.
```js
_.and = (...functions) => (...args) => functions.every((f) => f(...args));
_.or = (...functions) => (...args) => functions.some((f) => f(...args));
```

More complex implementation can be ability to use both values and functions.
```js
_.and = (...predicates) => (...args) => predicates.every((f) => _.isFunction(f) ? f(...args) : Boolean(f));
_.or = (...predicates) => (...args) => predicates.some((f) => _.isFunction(f) ? f(...args) : Boolean(f));
```
Example of usage:

```js
const isPositive = (v) => v > 0;
const isEven = (v) => v % 2  === 0;
const isPositiveAndEven = _.and(isPositive, isEven);
const isPositiveOrEven = _.or(isPositive, isEven);

isPositiveAndEven(-1); // false
isPositiveAndEven(1); // false
isPositiveAndEven(2); // true

isPositiveOrEven(-1); // false
isPositiveOrEven(1); // true
isPositiveOrEven(2); // true
```

